<subSubSection pageId="6" pageNumber="22" type="reference_group">
<paragraph blockId="6.[151,1437,1385,1527]" pageId="6" pageNumber="22">
<taxonomicName box="[151,293,1385,1410]" class="Insecta" family="Apidae" genus="Eucerinoda" kingdom="Animalia" order="Hymenoptera" pageId="6" pageNumber="22" phylum="Arthropoda" rank="genus">
<emphasis box="[151,293,1385,1410]" italics="true" pageId="6" pageNumber="22">Eucerinoda</emphasis>
</taxonomicName>
is a probably relictual monotypic genus, which is distributed exclusively in 
<collectingCountry box="[1235,1301,1385,1411]" name="Chile" pageId="6" pageNumber="22">Chile</collectingCountry>
(
<bibRefCitation author="Michener" pageId="6" pageNumber="30" refString="Michener, C. D. (1979) Biogeography of the bees. Annals of the Missouri Botanical Garden, 66, 277 - 347." type="journal article" year="1979">
Michener 
<number box="[151,215,1424,1450]" pageId="6" pageNumber="22" value="1979.0">1979</number>
</bibRefCitation>
). As mentioned by 
<bibRefCitation author="Michener" box="[446,648,1424,1450]" pageId="6" pageNumber="30" refString="Michener, C. D. (2007) The bees of the world (2 Â° Ed.). John Hopkins University Press, Baltimore, xvi + 992 pp." type="book" year="2007">
Michener (
<number box="[575,639,1424,1450]" pageId="6" pageNumber="22" value="2007.0">2007</number>
)
</bibRefCitation>
, 
<taxonomicName authority="Spinola" authorityName="Spinola" box="[661,977,1424,1450]" class="Insecta" family="Apidae" genus="Eucerinoda" kingdom="Animalia" order="Hymenoptera" pageId="6" pageNumber="22" phylum="Arthropoda" rank="species" species="gayi">
<emphasis box="[661,857,1424,1449]" italics="true" pageId="6" pageNumber="22">Eucerinoda gayi</emphasis>
(Spinola)
</taxonomicName>
, the only known species of this genus, has the paraglossa much shorter than first segment of labial palpus, and gradulus of S 
<number box="[1184,1200,1462,1488]" pageId="6" pageNumber="22" value="2.0">2</number>
simple and curved. These characters are unique within 
<taxonomicName box="[566,668,1501,1527]" class="Insecta" family="Apidae" kingdom="Animalia" order="Hymenoptera" pageId="6" pageNumber="22" phylum="Arthropoda" rank="tribe" tribe="Eucerini">Eucerini</taxonomicName>
, and justify its placement in its own subtribe: Eucerinodina.
</paragraph>
